snippet.textDisplay: For the new stations out to Reading, I don't like the term 'outside the fare zone, Oyster not valid' this is true but it doesn't say contactless is. It gives the impression they're outside the 'pay as you go' area. Don't forget to make use of the 'single fare finder' on the TfL website to compare fares for your journey compared with the national rail paper ticket fares. There are huge savings to be made especially for single journeys or if you travel early and 'touch in' before 06.30. Travelling to/from the new area there are now two fare structures. Same as to Gatwick on the Brighton line or Luton Airport on Thameslink. Examples. Paddington to Reading off-peak single with contactless £10.60. National rail paper ticket £21.20. Buyer beware. Victoria-Gatwick on Southern services Oyster/contactless off-peak £8.30. Paper ticket £16.70. Gatwick Express £19.80!!!

snippet.textDisplay: A different perspective of the Crossrail trains. There are no toilets on the trains, there do not appear to be seats with a table and there don’t seem to be sockets to plug phones in? The trains are freezing cold, in sense that the doors are open for ages and as the train is effectively one carriage a hurricane blows through the train generating a major draft and loosing all the heat in the train. The seats are really poorly upholstered, if travelling from Reading to Abbeywood better have cast iron buttocks. GWR trains are far superior and I think there are implications for Freedom pass users now being excluded from using some GWR services since the introduction of these trains. Progress?

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Geoff, a new TfL map could be double-sided. On one side have the Tube, DLR and Trams (turn up and go services) with Overground/Crossrail in faded lines only showing interchanges but no station markers or names. On the other side have the Overground and Crossrail (main line timetabled services) with Tube/DLR/Trams in faded lines only showing interchanges but no station markers or names.
Two maps showing different modes as priority but faintly showing the other services, makes both maps less cluttered.
